    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-12-21T17:32:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-12-21T17:32:00-05:00" n="667"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d667">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/303: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kaufman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">La Paz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-12-21T18:00:00-04:32"
                            >December 21, 1928—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>64. Department’s telegram 40, December 19, 6 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Bolivia willing to sign protocol.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Basis of protocol covered in points 3 to 8.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Bolivia would probably name two delegates.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Delegates from the United States, Argentine, Brazil, Uruguay and Peru or
                        Cuba are acceptable to Bolivia.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Bolivia is willing to have Commission settle the boundary dispute after
                        the present difficulty is disposed of.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>Bolivian army has already received orders not to advance or attack but to
                        maintain defense only.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>Bolivia favors Washington as a meeting place for the Commission.</item>
                    <label>8.</label>
                    <item>Bolivia is not disposed to renew diplomatic relations at present but
                        prefers to await opportune time after the Commission convenes.</item>
                </list>
                <p>The foregoing information is the personal opinion of Minister for Foreign
                    Affairs.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kaufman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
